fields.descriptive_line: soft back plastic covered Letts Girl Guide Diary, 1973 owned by Ellen (Eleanor) Lloyd.
fields.physical_description: A small pocket sized plastic soft back diary produced for the Girl Guides by publisher, Letts for the year 1973. The diary has not been used but the personal information  at the beginning has been filled in by its owner, Eleanor Lloyd. the diary is made of blue plastic with a transparent sleeve on the back to store notes. The front is embossed in gold print with the date, Girl Guide emblem and 'Letts Girl Guide Diary'.
fields.dimensions: Width: 7.5 cm, Height: 10.3 cm, Depth: 0.7 cm
fields.title: Letts Girl Guide Diary
fields.public_access_description:
The Girl Guides were set up by Robert Baden Powell in 1910 as a version of the Scouts for girls to join. They  were involved in a variety of activities similar to those of the Scout and would attend camps and do outdoors activities but there was also a strong focuss on domestic duties and skills such as cooking and cleaning. As with the Scouts and the Brownies, the Guides had a promise and their own 'law' that they should follow:
1. A guide is loyal and can be trusted.
2. A Guide is helpful.
3. A Guide is polite and considerate.
4. A Guide is friendly and a sister to all Guides.
5. A Guide is kind to animals and respects all living things.
6. A Guide is obedient.
7. A Guide has courage and is cheerful in all difficulties.
8. AGuide makes good use of her time.
9. A Guide takes care of her possessions and those of other people.
10. A Guide is self controlled in all she thinks, says, and does.
fields.history_note: Owned by Eleanor (Ellen) Lloyd when she was a Girl Guide in 1973-76. Eleanor has donated a number of Brownie and Guide related material to the museum that were owned or made by her or her 3 sisters in the 1970s.
